The Science Fiction Radio Show

00:36.380 --> 00:38.320
And here are your hosts.

00:42.500 --> 00:50.460
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. James Gunn approaches science fiction from
many angles. He writes it, he teaches it, and he's published important

00:50.460 --> 00:58.700
historical and critical material on science fiction. Some of Gunn's better-known
novels include The Joymakers, The Immortals, The Listeners, and The Dreamers.

00:58.700 --> 01:06.720
The Immortals was the basis for the television show of a few years back, The
Immortal. Gunn's critical work, in addition to numerous essays, consists of two

01:06.720 --> 01:15.020
major publications, Alternate Worlds, The 1975 History of Science Fiction, and
The Road to Science Fiction, the four-volume anthology that includes Gunn's

01:15.020 --> 01:21.780
essays on the definition of science fiction and its historical development.
Gunn's criticism is valuable because it not only comes from someone who knows

01:21.780 --> 01:29.840
the field, but also because Gunn is a scholar and professor at a major
university. he brings the insight of a professional academic to the field. We

01:29.840 --> 01:37.280
talked with Gunn about how he divides himself between being both a writer and a
teacher. We asked him if he'd ever considered writing as a full-time career. I

01:37.280 --> 01:53.520
did, as a matter of fact, write full-time for a period of a little more than
three years. A year in 1948, 1949, and I went back to school then and got a

01:53.520 --> 02:07.280
master's degree. but i continued to write and uh then uh after i'd worked for
this paperback publisher after i got my master's degree uh worked for a

02:07.280 --> 02:15.480
paperback publisher for a year and a half i found out that i'd sold four stories
that i hadn't known about and decided to go back to full time writing So I did

02:15.480 --> 02:37.880
write full-time from the fall of 1942 until the late summer of 1955. And really
much of the groundwork for the later books that I published and the success that

02:37.880 --> 02:50.740
I had, I think such as it was, was based upon that freelance period. I didn't
make a lot of money at it, below the poverty level, but my needs were fairly

02:50.740 --> 03:02.920
simple at that time. And what it later paid off in the sense that the stories
that I wrote appeared in books, and some of them even were made in the movies

03:02.920 --> 03:15.740
and all that sort of thing. Gunn explains how he became involved in teaching. It
was after 1955, or in the fall of 1955, after my wife and I had moved back to

03:15.740 --> 03:26.600
Lawrence, Kansas, simply as a place to live, but I got involved almost by
accident with teaching at the university, from which I'd gotten my two degrees

03:26.600 --> 03:38.000
at the University of Kansas, and became involved with other aspects of the
university, edited the alumni magazine for three years, and then became director

03:38.000 --> 03:49.120
of public relations for the university for 12 years before returning to full
-time teaching and writing in 1970. Gunn always intended to write science

03:49.120 --> 04:06.160
fiction criticism. But looking back upon it, I know, I think right from the
beginning, I had the feeling that I wanted to do criticism in the area My first

04:06.160 --> 04:21.000
ten stories, for instance, were published under a pseudonym of Edwin James. I
began to use my own name with the eleventh story. But the reason I can remember

04:21.000 --> 04:32.840
now for doing that was the fact that I thought I would write criticism about
science fiction, and I wanted to save my real name for that. But after ten

04:32.840 --> 04:47.760
stories, I decided that was foolish. and I ought to use my real name for
everything. But looking back upon it, I think the academic interest was there

04:47.760 --> 04:54.640
right from the beginning. Beginning next time, we'll talk with James Gunn about
his writing, both the stories and the criticism.

05:01.740 --> 05:09.660
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show. a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:09.660 --> 05:10.420
Odessa, Texas.

