06:24.780 --> 06:26.440
And here are your hosts.

06:30.760 --> 06:39.040
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. James Gunn, author, critic, and teacher of
science fiction, has written some valuable books on the definition and

06:39.040 --> 06:46.700
historical development of science fiction. He's examining some big questions in
this work. Things like what is science fiction? What makes it different from

06:46.700 --> 06:54.440
other literature? And where it comes from? And since Gunn is a professor at the
University of Kansas, besides being a long-time author of science fiction, he

06:54.440 --> 07:03.360
combines a scholar's objectivity and a creator's understanding in answering
these questions. alternate worlds published in 1976 is his first major critical

07:03.360 --> 07:14.720
work gunn explains its origin i had uh when i first went back to full-time
teaching had been asked if i would teach a science fiction course which is

07:14.720 --> 07:27.800
different from the experience at most universities where uh there is some
resistance to the notion of doing that and i accepted because i had the feeling

07:27.800 --> 07:43.540
that there wasn't a good history of science fiction and that this course would
give me the incentive to write it. So I sat down and wrote very fast and ended

07:43.540 --> 07:52.960
up with 13 chapters representing about 13 lectures for the 14-week semester.

07:54.140 --> 08:12.940
and these chapters or these lectures became the 13 chapters in a book of mine
which appeared in about I guess 75 after some delays as Alternate Worlds, the

08:12.940 --> 08:23.740
Illustrated History of Science Fiction but as it won consequence of its
publication I got a call one day from an editor at New American Library who was

08:23.740 --> 08:41.160
admiring it, and asked me if I'd like to do a book for them. And I knew also
that I really felt the need for anthologies which covered more than the brief

08:41.160 --> 08:57.060
span of the 20s to the 60s, which most anthologies did, and there really wasn't
much in the 20s or 30s, most of it covered the period of the 40s and 50s. So I

08:57.060 --> 09:12.420
said yes, and I sent them a proposal for the first volume of the rote science
fiction. At that time, all we knew that there would be would be one volume which

09:12.420 --> 09:30.640
covered a period from the earliest prehistory of literature, not to mention
science fiction. up to 1900 and the H.G. Wells Early Stories and Novels. The

09:30.640 --> 09:38.100
volume used a unique and valuable approach to science fiction criticism. It was
an anthology of stories. But each story was accompanied by an essay which

09:38.100 --> 09:46.280
covered the story's importance and also discussed the period of science fiction
history to which it belonged. Gunn explains how that volume led to others. By

09:46.280 --> 09:55.020
the time I got finished with the manuscript, I had felt that it really, unlike
most books, came out even better than I thought it was going to, and I proposed

09:55.020 --> 10:10.680
that we go ahead with a second and third volume. They said, let's wait and see
how this does. And eventually, after it had done better than they thought, they

10:10.680 --> 10:28.100
agreed that I could go on to volume two and three. uh, which, uh, covered the
period, uh, from, uh, 1900 to approximately 1940, and then from 1940 to 1970 or

10:28.100 --> 10:37.140
70, actually, the latest one, 76, I think. Gunn has recently published a fourth
volume in the series and says that it's now finished. The title for the entire

10:37.140 --> 10:44.280
series is The Road to Science Fiction, and it stands as a major work of science
fiction criticism. We'll talk some more about it with James Gunn next time.

10:51.320 --> 10:59.200
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:59.200 --> 10:59.940
Odessa, Texas.

