12:12.040 --> 12:13.540
And here are your hosts.

12:17.800 --> 12:25.460
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. James Gunn is noted not only as an author
of science fiction, but as a critic of the field and as a chronicler in the

12:25.460 --> 12:33.500
story of its development. Gunn has recently completed the last volume in his
four-volume series, The Road to Science Fiction. In this unique work, he traces

12:33.500 --> 12:40.620
the development of science fiction from the very beginning of recorded
literature until the present day. What's different and valuable about Gunn's

12:40.620 --> 12:47.720
approach in the road to science fiction is that he uses the actual literature
itself, from tales belonging to the ancient world and modern short stories. But

12:47.720 --> 12:55.860
each literary selection is accompanied by an essay which discusses the work's
importance and deals with the historical period to which it belongs. When using

12:55.860 --> 13:02.380
the volumes then, a reader not only is getting some good science fiction, but
he's picking up an education relating to the definition and development of

13:02.380 --> 13:11.020
science fiction. Except for the last one, Each volume is also organized around a
particular thesis or point. The first one, for instance, develops the idea that

13:11.020 --> 13:21.620
before real science fiction could exist, mankind had to recognize the concept of
change. It seems to me that the essential nature of science fiction is that it

13:21.620 --> 13:35.460
deals with change. In fact, in order for us to recognize a story or a novel as
being science fiction, We have to identify that part of it which is different

13:35.460 --> 13:46.820
from here and now, our everyday world. And so it deals with how people would
react in changed circumstances.

13:49.460 --> 14:04.780
So up to approximately the time of the Investor Revolution, the very concept of
change itself was alien to human minds. It seems to me, looking back over the

14:04.780 --> 14:24.240
history of humanity, that mostly people saw change as being only the eternal
circle of the seasons changing from spring to summer to fall to winter and back

14:24.240 --> 14:38.000
again. And it wasn't until the Investor Revolution and, of course, the
scientific perceptions that preceded it and accompanied it, which began to

14:38.000 --> 14:52.800
create change that people saw could be beneficial over which they might be able
to exercise some control. That is, it was man-made change created by human

14:52.800 --> 15:08.260
desires and intelligence, and it could be controlled by humanity's exercise of
intelligence. And it seems to me that science fiction was the literary response

15:08.260 --> 15:18.020
to that recognition. The next two volumes develop other ideas that Gunn believes
are essential to the development of science fiction. The notion, for instance,

15:18.140 --> 15:25.800
that mankind is a species rather than isolated tribes or nations or races. But
the last volume is a bit different. This is because it deals with the most

15:25.800 --> 15:34.320
recent science fiction stories, and it's more difficult to tell which ones will
be important. In the more current story, this is much more difficult to

15:34.320 --> 15:45.840
determine. You can't really say what stories are important until much after
they've been published, and you can't certainly say which are typical until you

15:45.840 --> 16:00.920
decide what the period really stands for. So what I did in the fourth volume was
to select stories that I thought dealt with the literary uses of science

16:00.920 --> 16:13.100
fiction. And so the volume is primarily concerned not with questions of generic
importance, but the question of literary uses. Gunn has performed a valuable

16:13.100 --> 16:20.280
service to the field with the four volumes in his The Road to Science Fiction
series. By defining science fiction, by demonstrating what makes it different

16:20.280 --> 16:28.800
from other types of literature, and by revealing its origins, he's made science
fiction more understandable and more respectable. Next time, we'll talk with

16:28.800 --> 16:29.880
Gunn about his own fiction.

16:37.260 --> 16:45.160
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:45.160 --> 16:47.640
Odessa, Texas.

