18:03.680 --> 18:12.680
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. In much of his science fiction, James Gunn
examines the question of what makes man happy. He extrapolates a future which

18:12.680 --> 18:21.240
seems plausible from current social conditions and asked the standard science
fiction question, What If? In his 1963 novel, The Joymakers, he fills out the

18:21.240 --> 18:29.120
question by asking what if man discovered a drug that would make him perfectly
happy, even though it would remove him from the real world. Gunn answers the

18:29.120 --> 18:37.800
question by saying that man would probably accept the opportunity. And then he
shows what would happen to man and society as a result. Ultimately, as it worked

18:37.800 --> 18:47.060
out in the novel, it turned out that the people who wanted happiness to get what
they want,

18:50.060 --> 19:01.020
since what one can get in the external world is limited by the number of people
and the number of people who want this particular thing. Ultimately, they get

19:01.020 --> 19:16.320
what they want by being fed illusions that they get what they want. And
ultimately, everybody ends up floating in amniotic cells living on dreams of

19:16.320 --> 19:28.820
success and accomplishment fed by a machine, which eventually works out to be
that you're happy when you don't want anything anymore. And it occurred to me

19:28.820 --> 19:42.880
that that is the same as death, and ultimately the equation for that is that
happiness equals death, and that life is still wanting something. One of Gunn's

19:42.880 --> 19:52.020
more recent books, The Dreamers, also published in paperback as The Mind Master,
also presents a society in which man has presumably achieved perfect happiness.

19:52.360 --> 20:00.720
And he does so through chemical memory. Any possible experience can be felt by
an individual if he is injected with the DNA or RNA of someone who has actually

20:00.720 --> 20:19.240
undergone that experience. It is a comment on the fact that that dreaming itself
is a non-survival characteristic. It may be the most satisfying, ultimately the

20:19.240 --> 20:32.160
most satisfying experience, but as perhaps I said in The Joymakers, is perhaps
repeated here in a different way, that ultimate satisfaction or dreaming is a

20:32.160 --> 20:38.500
death activity, and that survival

20:38.500 --> 20:50.580
demands something less than total satisfaction. Both The Joymakers and The
Dreamers, along with many of Gunn's other books, consist of a series of related

20:50.580 --> 20:58.880
novellas rather than being a straightforward novel. Gunn says that he started
this practice years ago, not long after he began writing science fiction, for a

20:58.880 --> 21:06.460
couple of reasons. It allowed him to be paid twice, since he could publish each
novella separately in a magazine before putting it with other novellas to make

21:06.460 --> 21:18.960
up a whole novel. And as a consequence, I have since that time mostly written my
novels in the form of publishable

21:18.960 --> 21:33.220
fragments or individual stories. And in a way, I think it's worked rather well
because in The Joymakers, I was able to use as a framework, as a subject matter,

21:33.420 --> 21:45.740
really an idea rather than a person or a group of people. And so this novel,
which extended over about 200 years, picked up several different people, but

21:45.740 --> 21:55.580
basically was about one thing, The Science of Happiness. and similarly The
Immortals, which also continued for about 200 years, and The Listeners, which

21:55.580 --> 22:02.460
covered about 150 years. And all

22:02.460 --> 22:12.560
of these seem to me to focus on an idea, which is what science fiction mostly
does. We'll continue with the work of James Gunn next time.

22:19.880 --> 22:27.720
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
